-- PRESS DIGEST - Bulgaria - Oct 31
-- 
-- Fri Oct 31, 2014 04:08AM EDT
-- None



SOFIA, Oct 31 (Reuters) - These are some of the main stories in Bulgarian newspapers on Friday. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

-- Leaders of the centre-right GERB and the right-wing Reformist Bloc said they are ready to strike a coalition agreement. Nationalist Patriotic Front and centre-left ABV are expecting to support the government (Presa, Monitor, Sega, 24 Chasa, Capital daily). 24 CHASA - Bulgaria and Austria both believe Europe needs energy diversification and support a South Stream gas pipeline project that would comply with EU law, Bulgarian President Rosen Plevneliev and Austrian head of state Heinz Fischer said after their meeting in Sofia.  -- Chief Prosecutor Sotir Tsatsarov will submit early next month demands that seven lawmakers and a Member of the European Parliament be stripped of immunity. He refused to disclose any names (Standart, 24 Chasa, Monitor, Duma). -- Interim Defence Minister Velizar Shalamanov admitted there are Bulgarian citizens fighting on the side of the Islamic State (IS) (Presa, Standart, Sega, Monitor, Duma). -- Interim Interior Minister Yordan Bakalov said he was ready to retain the post in the next government, but "on certain conditions" (Standart, Sega, 24 Chasa).  -- The efforts of the interior ministry have been aimed at countering human trafficking since the beginning of August, Interim Interior Minister Yordan Bakalov said. Some 472 people had been arrested on suspicion of human trafficking since the beginning of 2014, with 218 of the total detained in August and September (Sega, 24 Chasa, Duma). -- An unnamed investor expressed readiness to help the troubled Corporative Commercial Bank (Corpbank) with 1 billion euros (1.26 billion US dollar), Menda Stoyanova, the head of the parliamentary budget commission  said (Standart, Sega, 24 Chasa, Capital daily, Duma).